var tafsirData_8 = {
  1: {
    "They ask you ˹O Prophet˺ regarding the spoils of war.": "After the Battle of Badr, the Muslim fighters had disagreements about how to divide the war gains. Some wanted more than others, and disputes arose among them. So they came to the Prophet Muhammad ﷺ asking for a ruling on this matter. This verse was revealed to settle the dispute and teach an important lesson about submission to Allah's commands.",
    "Say, \"Their distribution is decided by Allah and His Messenger.": "The Prophet ﷺ is instructed to tell them clearly that the decision about war spoils belongs entirely to Allah and His Messenger. This means no individual has the right to claim more based on their own reasoning or desires. The ruling will come from divine guidance, not human preferences. This teaches Muslims that in matters where Allah has given a ruling, personal opinions must be set aside.",
    "So be mindful of Allah,": "Before anything else, they are commanded to have taqwa (God-consciousness). This means being aware that Allah is watching, and acting with reverence and caution. When believers remember that Allah sees everything, they become less focused on worldly gains and more concerned with pleasing Him.",
    "settle your affairs,": "This is a command to fix the disputes and disagreements that had arisen among them. Unity and brotherhood are more valuable than material gains. The Prophet ﷺ said: \"Do not hate one another, do not envy one another, and do not turn your backs on one another. Be servants of Allah, as brothers.\" (Sahih Muslim). Disputes over money can destroy relationships, so Allah commands reconciliation first.",
    "and obey Allah and His Messenger if you are ˹true˺ believers.\"": "True faith is proven through obedience. Anyone can claim to believe, but real belief is shown when a person accepts Allah's commands even when they conflict with personal desires. If they truly believe, they will submit willingly to whatever Allah and His Messenger decide, without complaint or resentment."
  },
  2: {
    "The ˹true˺ believers are only those whose hearts tremble at the remembrance of Allah,": "When Allah's name is mentioned, or when they are reminded of His commands, warnings, or greatness, their hearts are moved with a mixture of awe, fear, and love. This is not a physical shaking, but a spiritual stirring—a softness and humility that enters the heart. For example, when someone is about to commit a sin and then remembers that Allah is watching, a true believer's heart will tremble and pull back. This is a sign of a living, responsive heart.",
    "whose faith increases when His revelations are recited to them,": "Faith (iman) is not static—it goes up and down. When true believers hear the Quran being recited, their faith grows stronger. They feel more connected to Allah, more certain of the truth, and more motivated to do good. The Quran acts like nourishment for the soul. Just as food strengthens the body, the words of Allah strengthen the heart. The companions would weep when hearing the Quran because it deeply affected them.",
    "and who put their trust in their Lord.": "Tawakkul (trust in Allah) means relying completely on Allah while also taking the necessary actions. A true believer does their best, then leaves the outcome to Allah without excessive worry. For instance, a farmer plants seeds, waters them, and then trusts Allah for the harvest. This trust brings peace of mind because the believer knows Allah's plan is always best, even if things don't go as expected."
  },
  3: {
    "˹They are˺ those who establish prayer": "Establishing prayer is more than just performing it mechanically. It means praying consistently at the proper times, with proper focus (khushu'), fulfilling all its conditions and pillars, and allowing it to impact one's behavior. Prayer is the direct connection between the servant and Allah. The Prophet ﷺ said: \"The first thing the servant will be held accountable for on the Day of Judgment is the prayer.\" (Sunan an-Nasa'i). A person who truly establishes prayer stays away from evil because the prayer itself prohibits indecency.",
    "and donate from what We have provided for them.": "True believers spend from their wealth in the way of Allah—whether as obligatory charity (zakat) or voluntary charity (sadaqah). Notice Allah says \"from what We have provided\"—reminding us that all wealth ultimately belongs to Allah. We are just trustees. Giving charity purifies the heart from greed and attachment to worldly possessions. It also helps those in need and builds a caring community. The Prophet ﷺ said: \"Charity does not decrease wealth.\" (Sahih Muslim)."
  },
  4: {
    "It is they who are the true believers.": "Allah confirms that those who have the qualities mentioned in the previous verses—hearts that tremble, faith that increases, trust in Allah, establishing prayer, and giving charity—these are the genuine believers. This is not just a label; it is a reality confirmed by Allah Himself. Others may claim faith, but these are the ones whose faith is real and complete.",
    "They will have elevated ranks,": "In the Hereafter, they will have high levels in Paradise. Not all believers are equal—those who strive more and have stronger faith will have higher positions. The Prophet ﷺ described that the people of Paradise will see those above them like we see distant stars, because of the difference in their ranks. (Sahih Bukhari).",
    "forgiveness,": "Despite their high status, they are still human and make mistakes. So Allah promises them forgiveness for their sins. This shows Allah's mercy—even the best believers need His forgiveness, and He grants it generously to those who sincerely believe and do good.",
    "and an honourable provision from their Lord.": "They will receive a generous, noble sustenance in Paradise—food, drink, and pleasures that are pure and dignified. Unlike worldly provisions that can be earned through dishonest means, the provision of Paradise is completely honorable and blessed. It represents the best of rewards from the Most Generous Lord."
  },
  5: {
    "Similarly, when your Lord brought you ˹O Prophet˺ out of your home for a just cause,": "This refers to when the Prophet ﷺ left Madinah heading towards Badr. Allah guided him to confront the Quraysh caravan, and later the Quraysh army. The phrase \"for a just cause\" (bil-haqq) means this mission was based on truth and divine wisdom. It was not a random decision—it was Allah's plan to establish Islam and weaken its enemies. The Prophet ﷺ was acting on Allah's command.",
    "a group of believers was totally against it.": "Not all the companions were enthusiastic about this mission. Some of them were reluctant because they had not prepared for a battle—they thought they were only going to intercept a trade caravan, which would be easier and less dangerous. When they learned they might face the well-armed Quraysh army, some felt afraid and unwilling. This shows that even believers can have moments of weakness or hesitation, but what matters is that they ultimately submitted to Allah's command."
  },
  6: {
    "They disputed with you about the truth after it had been made clear,": "Even after it became clear that Allah wanted them to confront the enemy army (not just the caravan), some continued to argue and express their reluctance. The truth had been made plain through divine revelation, yet they still debated. This teaches us that sometimes people resist what is clearly right because of fear or attachment to comfort. However, a believer should accept Allah's decree once it becomes clear.",
    "as if they were being driven to death with their eyes wide open.": "This powerful imagery describes their extreme fear. They looked as terrified as people being dragged to their execution while fully conscious. The fear of death overwhelmed them to this degree. This is a natural human emotion, but the verse implicitly reminds us that death is in Allah's hands alone. Those who trust Allah know that no one dies before their appointed time. Eventually, these believers overcame their fear and fought bravely at Badr, proving that initial weakness doesn't define a person—what matters is the final choice."
  },
  7: {
    "˹Remember, O believers,˺ when Allah promised ˹to give˺ you the upper hand over either target,": "Allah had promised the Muslims victory over one of two groups: either the Quraysh trade caravan (which had valuable goods but few guards) or the Quraysh army (which was heavily armed and dangerous). Both were targets, and Allah guaranteed success over one of them.",
    "you wished to capture the unarmed party.": "Naturally, the Muslims preferred the easier option—the trade caravan with its wealth and minimal resistance. This was a practical human desire. They were few in number, poorly equipped, and hadn't prepared for a major battle. Wanting the easier path wasn't sinful, but Allah had a greater plan.",
    "But it was Allah's Will to establish the truth by His Words": "Allah wanted more than just material gain for the Muslims. He wanted to establish Islam firmly through a decisive confrontation. His \"Words\" refer to His decrees, promises, and the revelation that would be proven true through this victory. The Battle of Badr would become a defining moment in Islamic history.",
    "and uproot the disbelievers;": "Allah intended to cut off and weaken the leaders of disbelief. Many of the worst enemies of Islam—like Abu Jahl—were killed at Badr. This broke the power of those who had persecuted Muslims for years. Allah's plan was comprehensive: not just a small gain, but a transformative victory that would change the course of history."
  },
  8: {
    "to firmly establish the truth and wipe out falsehood—": "The purpose of this battle was to make the truth of Islam manifest and undeniable, while exposing and destroying the falsehood of idolatry and oppression. Badr proved that Allah supports His believers and that Islam was not a passing movement but a divinely-backed mission. Truth became established through this miraculous victory.",
    "even to the dismay of the wicked.": "The criminals and enemies of Islam hated this outcome, but their hatred couldn't prevent Allah's plan. This is a universal principle: no matter how much people of falsehood resist, scheme, or fight against the truth, Allah will make His truth prevail. Their displeasure is irrelevant to Allah's decree."
  },
  9: {
    "˹Remember˺ when you cried out to your Lord for help,": "Before the battle began, the Muslims saw the size and strength of the enemy army—about 1,000 well-equipped fighters against roughly 313 Muslims with limited weapons. In this desperate moment, they turned to Allah in sincere supplication, begging for His help. The Prophet ﷺ himself made intense du'a, raising his hands until his cloak fell off his shoulders, saying: \"O Allah, if this small group is destroyed, You will not be worshipped on earth.\" (Sahih Muslim). This teaches us that in times of difficulty, our first response should be turning to Allah.",
    "He answered, \"I will reinforce you with a thousand angels—followed by many others.\"": "Allah responded to their desperate prayer by sending angels to fight alongside them. Initially, a thousand angels came, and then more followed in waves. The angels fought in the battle, striking the disbelievers and supporting the believers. Some companions reported seeing the marks of angelic strikes on the bodies of the enemy. This was a direct, miraculous intervention from Allah."
  },
  10: {
    "And Allah made this a sign of victory and reassurance to your hearts.": "The sending of angels served two purposes: it was good news (bushra) that promised victory, and it brought calmness and confidence to the believers' hearts. Knowing that angels were fighting alongside them removed their fear and doubt. This shows how Allah cares for both the physical and emotional needs of His servants.",
    "Victory comes only from Allah.": "This is a crucial reminder. Despite the presence of angels and the efforts of the believers, ultimate victory belongs to Allah alone. No amount of military strategy, numbers, or strength can guarantee success—only Allah grants victory. This keeps believers humble and prevents arrogance after any success.",
    "Surely Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.": "He is Al-Aziz (Almighty)—no one can overpower Him or resist His will. And He is Al-Hakeem (All-Wise)—every decision He makes is based on perfect wisdom. The timing of the battle, the way it was fought, and the outcome were all part of Allah's wise plan."
  },
  11: {
    "˹Remember˺ when He caused drowsiness to overcome you, giving you serenity.": "The night before the Battle of Badr, Allah blessed the believers with a peaceful sleep. Despite the terrifying situation ahead, they were able to rest. This drowsiness was a gift from Allah—a sign of inner peace and security. Normally, fear keeps people awake, but Allah calmed their hearts so they could sleep and wake refreshed for battle. Ali ibn Abi Talib (may Allah be pleased with him) said: \"On the night of Badr, all of us slept except the Messenger of Allah ﷺ, who prayed under a tree until dawn.\"",
    "And He sent down rain from the sky to purify you,": "Allah sent rain that benefited the Muslims in multiple ways. First, it allowed them to purify themselves for prayer (making wudu and ghusl), which strengthened their spiritual state before the fight.",
    "free you from Satan's whispers,": "Before the battle, Shaytan was trying to instill fear and doubt in their hearts, whispering that they would be defeated and destroyed. The rain and the sleep removed these evil whispers, replacing anxiety with confidence. Spiritual purity and peace of mind go together.",
    "strengthen your hearts,": "The rain gave them courage and determination. When a person is spiritually cleansed and rested, their heart becomes stronger. They were now emotionally and spiritually ready to face a much larger enemy.",
    "and make ˹your˺ steps firm.": "The battlefield at Badr had sandy ground. Without rain, the Muslims would have sunk into the sand, making movement difficult. But the rain firmed up the ground on their side, allowing them to stand and move steadily. Meanwhile, the side where the disbelievers camped became muddy and difficult. Allah used nature itself to support the believers."
  },
  12: {
    "˹Remember, O Prophet,˺ when your Lord revealed to the angels, \"I am with you.": "Allah communicated directly with the angels, assuring them of His support. When Allah says \"I am with you,\" it means His help, guidance, and power are with them. The angels were not acting independently—they were carrying out Allah's command with His backing.",
    "So make the believers stand firm.": "The angels were commanded to strengthen the hearts of the Muslim fighters—giving them courage, resolve, and steadfastness in battle. This support was both spiritual (inner strength) and possibly physical (helping in the fighting). The believers didn't see the angels directly in most cases, but they felt the effects of their presence.",
    "I will cast horror into the hearts of the disbelievers.": "Allah Himself placed terror in the hearts of the Quraysh army. Despite their superior numbers and equipment, they were overcome with fear. This psychological warfare came from Allah, not from any human strategy. When Allah decides to help His people, He can defeat enemies through their own emotions.",
    "So strike their necks and strike their fingertips.\"": "The angels were given permission to fight. Striking the necks means killing blows, and striking the fingertips would disable their ability to hold weapons. This was divine instruction for the angels to participate actively in the battle."
  },
  13: {
    "This is because they defied Allah and His Messenger.": "The harsh punishment came because the Quraysh actively opposed Allah and His Messenger ﷺ. They had tortured Muslims, driven them from their homes, stolen their property, and waged war against Islam. Their punishment was a direct consequence of their defiance.",
    "And whoever defies Allah and His Messenger, then ˹know that˺ Allah is surely severe in punishment.": "This is a universal warning. Anyone who opposes Allah and His Messenger—whether through disbelief, persecution of believers, or fighting against Islam—will face severe consequences. Allah's punishment is not to be taken lightly. This serves as a warning to all who might consider opposing the truth."
  },
  14: {
    "That ˹worldly punishment˺ is yours, so taste it!": "This is addressed to the disbelievers who faced defeat and death at Badr. The punishment they received—defeat, humiliation, and death—was just the beginning. They are told to \"taste\" it as a consequence of their actions.",
    "Then the disbelievers will suffer the torment of the Fire.": "Beyond the worldly punishment, a far worse fate awaits them: the punishment of Hellfire in the Hereafter. Their suffering at Badr was temporary; the Fire is eternal. This emphasizes that opposing Allah leads to loss in both worlds."
  },
  15: {
    "O believers! When you face the disbelievers in battle,": "Allah addresses the believers with a direct command regarding warfare. When Muslims meet the enemy in battle formation, advancing toward each other, a specific rule applies.",
    "never turn your backs to them.": "Fleeing from the battlefield is strictly forbidden. Turning one's back to the enemy in retreat (except in specific circumstances) is a major sin. This is because fleeing demoralizes fellow fighters, shows weakness, and represents a failure to trust in Allah. The Prophet ﷺ listed fleeing from battle among the seven destructive sins. (Sahih Bukhari)"
  },
  16: {
    "And whoever does so on such an occasion—": "Anyone who turns their back and flees from battle—",
    "unless it is a manoeuvre": "There is an exception: tactical retreat is allowed. If a fighter pretends to flee to draw the enemy into a trap, or repositions to gain a strategic advantage, this is not considered fleeing. Military strategy is permitted.",
    "or to join their own troops—": "Another exception is moving to join another group of Muslim fighters. If a soldier leaves one unit to reinforce or join another, this is also acceptable. The intention is not to escape but to continue fighting from a different position.",
    "will earn the displeasure of Allah,": "Anyone who flees out of cowardice earns Allah's anger. This is one of the most serious sins because it combines cowardice, betrayal of fellow believers, and lack of trust in Allah.",
    "and their home will be Hell. What an evil destination!": "The punishment for fleeing from battle is Hellfire. This severe consequence shows how seriously Islam takes the duty to defend the faith and stand firm when facing enemies. Hell is described as the worst possible destination."
  },
  17: {
    "It was not you ˹believers˺ who killed them, but it was Allah Who did so.": "Although the Muslims physically fought and killed enemies at Badr, Allah reminds them that He was the true cause of their success. Their swords struck, but Allah guided those strikes. Their arrows hit, but Allah directed them. This prevents arrogance and ensures that all credit goes to Allah. The believers were instruments; Allah was the Doer.",
    "Nor was it you ˹O Prophet˺ who threw ˹a handful of sand at the disbelievers˺, but it was Allah Who did so,": "At Badr, the Prophet ﷺ threw a handful of sand or dust toward the enemy, saying: \"May their faces be deformed.\" This sand miraculously reached the eyes and mouths of the enemy fighters, causing confusion and distress. But Allah clarifies: even this act was enabled by Him. The Prophet ﷺ threw, but Allah made it reach every enemy. No human could throw that far or affect so many—it was divine intervention.",
    "rendering the believers a great favour.": "This victory was a beautiful trial and blessing from Allah. He tested the believers with battle, but blessed them with success, spoils, and increased faith. Good trials strengthen believers and bring them rewards.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah heard their prayers before the battle and knew their intentions and efforts. He hears every supplication and knows every heart. This is why He helped them—He knew their sincerity."
  },
  18: {
    "As such, Allah frustrates the evil plans of the disbelievers.": "No matter how the enemies of Islam plan and plot, Allah renders their schemes weak and ineffective. The Quraysh came to Badr confident in their numbers and strength, planning to crush the Muslims forever. But Allah turned their plans to dust. This is a recurring pattern: Allah always weakens and ultimately defeats the plots of those who oppose His religion."
  },
  19: {
    "If you ˹Meccans˺ sought judgment, now it has come to you.": "Before Badr, Abu Jahl and other Quraysh leaders arrogantly prayed at the Ka'bah, asking Allah to destroy whichever group was wrong. They were confident that they were right and that the Muslims would be destroyed. Allah answers them here with bitter irony: \"You asked for a verdict? Here it is!\" The verdict went against them—they were defeated, and many were killed.",
    "And if you cease, it will be for your own good.": "Despite their crime, Allah offers them a chance. If they stop fighting against Islam and stop their hostility, it will be better for them. This shows Allah's mercy—even after such a crushing defeat, the door to repentance remains open.",
    "But if you persist, We will persist.": "If they continue their aggression and return to fight the Muslims again, Allah will continue to support the believers and defeat the disbelievers. This is a warning: don't think Badr was a one-time event. Allah's help will come again and again.",
    "And your forces—no matter how numerous they might be—will not benefit you whatsoever.": "Numbers don't matter when Allah decides an outcome. The Quraysh had more men, better weapons, and more resources at Badr—yet they lost. Even if they gather larger armies in the future, it won't help them if Allah is against them.",
    "For Allah is certainly with the believers.": "This is the decisive factor: Allah's support is with those who believe in Him and follow His Messenger. As long as the believers remain faithful and obedient, Allah's help is guaranteed. This is the ultimate source of confidence for Muslims throughout history."
  },
  20: {
    "O believers! Obey Allah and His Messenger": "This is a fundamental command that appears repeatedly in the Quran. Believing in Allah requires obeying His commands. And obeying Allah means obeying His Messenger ﷺ, because the Prophet ﷺ only conveyed what Allah revealed to him. The two cannot be separated—you cannot claim to obey Allah while ignoring the Sunnah.",
    "and do not turn away from him while you hear ˹his call˺.": "Don't ignore the Prophet's teachings while you have access to them. The companions heard the Prophet ﷺ directly; later generations hear through the preserved Quran and Hadith. Turning away means ignoring, neglecting, or dismissing his guidance. This is especially serious because the truth has reached you—ignorance is no longer an excuse."
  },
  21: {
    "Do not be like those who say, \"We hear,\" but in fact they are not listening.": "This describes hypocrites and insincere people who claim to listen but don't actually absorb or act on what they hear. They go through the motions—attending gatherings, nodding along—but their hearts are elsewhere. True listening means understanding, accepting, and implementing what you hear. The Quran criticizes empty claims of obedience that aren't backed by action."
  },
  22: {
    "Indeed, the worst of all beings in the sight of Allah are the ˹wilfully˺ deaf and dumb, who do not understand.": "Allah declares that the worst creatures are not animals, but humans who refuse to use their faculties properly. They can hear but choose to be deaf to the truth. They can speak but refuse to say what is right. They have minds but refuse to think and understand. This is worse than actual disability because it is a deliberate choice. Animals follow their nature, but these people reject guidance that could save them."
  },
  23: {
    "Had Allah known any goodness in them, He would have certainly made them hear.": "If these people had any genuine goodness or potential for faith in their hearts, Allah would have opened their ears to the truth. But Allah knows what is in every heart, and He knew that they had no sincere desire for guidance.",
    "˹But˺ even if He had made them hear, they would have surely turned away heedlessly.": "Even if Allah had forced them to hear and understand the message, they would have rejected it anyway out of arrogance and stubbornness. Their problem wasn't lack of information—it was lack of willingness. This teaches us that guidance requires a receptive heart. No amount of evidence convinces someone who has already decided to reject the truth."
  },
  24: {
    "O believers! Respond to Allah and His Messenger when he calls you to that which gives you life.": "When Allah and His Messenger ﷺ call you to something, respond immediately and enthusiastically. What they call you to is described as \"that which gives you life.\" This means spiritual life—the life of the heart through faith, knowledge, and obedience. It also includes physical well-being through following Allah's laws. Islam is not a burden; it is the source of true life. Without it, a person may be physically alive but spiritually dead. An example: jihad in Allah's cause was being called for, and while it might seem to lead to death, in reality, it leads to eternal life in Paradise.",
    "And know that Allah stands between a person and their heart,": "This is a profound and somewhat frightening statement. Allah has complete control over human hearts. He can change a person's feelings, inclinations, and even their faith. A person might intend to do good, but Allah can prevent their heart from following through. This should make us constantly ask Allah to keep our hearts firm on guidance. The Prophet ﷺ frequently made this du'a: \"O Turner of hearts, keep my heart firm on Your religion.\" (Sahih Muslim)",
    "and that to Him you will all be gathered.": "Ultimately, everyone returns to Allah for judgment. This reminder puts everything in perspective. Whatever happens in this life—battles, disputes, gains, losses—is temporary. The final gathering before Allah is what truly matters."
  },
  25: {
    "Beware of a trial that will not only affect the wrongdoers among you.": "This is a serious warning about communal punishment. When sin becomes widespread and people don't forbid evil, a punishment may come that affects everyone—not just the sinners. The innocent suffer along with the guilty when they fail to stand against wrongdoing. For example, if corruption spreads in a society and no one speaks out, economic collapse or social breakdown may harm everyone. The Prophet ﷺ said: \"If people see an oppressor and do not stop him, Allah will soon punish them all.\" (Sunan Abu Dawud)",
    "And know that Allah is severe in punishment.": "This reinforces the warning. Allah's punishment is not something to take lightly. When it comes, it is severe and comprehensive. This should motivate believers to actively enjoin good and forbid evil in their communities."
  },
  26: {
    "Remember when you had been vastly outnumbered and oppressed in the land,": "Allah reminds the believers of their earlier condition in Makkah. They were a small, weak minority. The powerful Quraysh oppressed them, tortured them, and killed some of them. They had no protection, no wealth, and no military power.",
    "constantly in fear of attacks by your enemy,": "They lived in constant fear of being attacked, kidnapped, or killed. The Quraysh could strike at any moment, and there was no one to defend the early Muslims. Some were forced to hide their faith.",
    "then He sheltered you,": "Allah provided them with a safe haven—Madinah. The people of Madinah (the Ansar) welcomed the Muslims, gave them homes, and protected them. This migration (Hijrah) was a turning point.",
    "strengthened you with His help,": "Allah supported them with His divine help, including the victory at Badr and other battles. He sent angels, gave them courage, and caused their enemies to fear them.",
    "and provided you with good things": "After being poor and persecuted, the Muslims began to prosper. They received war spoils, their trade flourished, and they lived in security and abundance.",
    "so perhaps you would be thankful.": "All these blessings came so that the believers would be grateful to Allah. Gratitude is not just saying \"Alhamdulillah\"—it means recognizing Allah's favors and using His blessings in obedience to Him. Ingratitude for blessings can cause them to be taken away."
  },
  27: {
    "O believers! Do not betray Allah and the Messenger,": "Betraying Allah means violating His commands and committing sins. Betraying the Messenger ﷺ means abandoning his Sunnah, disobeying his orders, or working against the interests of Islam. This includes actions like sharing secrets with enemies, breaking covenants, or being disloyal to the Muslim community.",
    "nor betray your trusts knowingly.": "Every Muslim has trusts (amanah) to uphold: religious duties, family responsibilities, professional obligations, secrets entrusted to them, and community duties. Betraying any of these knowingly is a serious sin. The Prophet ﷺ said: \"The signs of a hypocrite are three: when he speaks, he lies; when he promises, he breaks it; and when he is trusted, he betrays.\" (Sahih Bukhari)"
  },
  28: {
    "And know that your wealth and your children are only a test": "Two of the things people love most—money and children—are described as tests (fitnah). They can lead a person toward good or toward evil. Some people betray trusts to gain more wealth or to benefit their children. Others neglect religious duties because they're busy earning money or raising families. This verse reminds us that these blessings are trials to see how we handle them. Will we let them distract us from Allah, or will we use them in His obedience?",
    "and that with Allah is a great reward.": "Whatever we might gain through betrayal or disobedience is nothing compared to what Allah has in store for the faithful. His reward is far greater and everlasting. So a believer should never sacrifice their eternal reward for temporary worldly gains."
  },
  29: {
    "O believers! If you are mindful of Allah,": "Taqwa (being mindful/conscious of Allah) is the key to countless blessings. It means living with awareness that Allah sees everything you do and judges everything you intend. Taqwa leads to avoiding sin and rushing toward good deeds.",
    "He will grant you a standard ˹to distinguish between right and wrong˺,": "Furqan means a criterion or standard that helps you distinguish truth from falsehood, right from wrong, beneficial from harmful. When you have taqwa, Allah grants you insight and wisdom. You begin to see through deceptions that fool others. Your heart becomes enlightened, and you make better decisions. This is one of the greatest gifts—spiritual clarity.",
    "absolve you of your sins,": "Allah will cover and remove your sins. The word \"kaffara\" means to wipe away or cover up. Your past mistakes will be erased from your record.",
    "and forgive you.": "Beyond removing sins, Allah also grants forgiveness (maghfirah), which includes protection from the punishment of those sins. It's a complete pardon.",
    "And Allah is the Lord of infinite bounty.": "Allah's favor and generosity have no limits. He gives more than we deserve and more than we can imagine. Taqwa unlocks access to this infinite bounty."
  },
  30: {
    "And ˹remember, O Prophet,˺ when the disbelievers conspired to capture, kill, or exile you.": "This refers to the night of the Hijrah, when the Quraysh leaders gathered in Dar al-Nadwa (their council house) to decide what to do about the Prophet ﷺ. They debated three options: (1) capture and imprison him forever, (2) kill him, or (3) expel him from Makkah. They eventually decided to kill him, with one young man from each tribe participating so that no single clan could be blamed. That night, they surrounded his house, planning to attack him when he came out.",
    "They planned, but Allah also planned.": "The Quraysh had their scheme, but Allah had His own plan. That night, Allah commanded the Prophet ﷺ to leave, and miraculously, he walked right past the assassins undetected while Ali ibn Abi Talib slept in his bed. Allah put sleep over their eyes and caused them not to see the Prophet ﷺ leaving. He even threw dust on their heads while reciting: \"And We have put a barrier before them and a barrier behind them and covered them, so they do not see.\" (Surah Ya-Sin: 9)",
    "And Allah is the best of planners.": "No matter how clever or powerful the enemies of Islam are, Allah's plan always prevails. He is the best of planners—His plans are perfect, His timing is precise, and His power is unmatched. The Prophet ﷺ escaped safely to Madinah, Islam flourished, and eventually the very people who tried to kill him submitted to Islam or were defeated. This is a source of comfort for all believers: when people conspire against you, know that Allah is planning too, and His plan is always better."
  },
  31: {
    "Whenever Our revelations are recited to them, they challenge ˹you˺, \"We have already heard ˹the recitation˺.": "When the Quran was recited to the Meccan pagans, instead of listening with open hearts, they responded with arrogance and dismissal. They claimed they had already heard such things before, implying it was nothing new or special. This was a tactic to discourage others from paying attention to the message. One of those who made such claims was al-Nadr ibn al-Harith, a Quraysh leader who had traveled widely and heard many stories.",
    "If we wanted, we could have easily produced something similar.": "This was a boastful lie. They claimed they could produce something like the Quran if they wished. Yet Allah challenged them repeatedly to produce even one chapter like it, and they never could. The Quran says: \"Say, 'If all mankind and jinn gathered together to produce the like of this Quran, they could not produce the like of it, even if they helped one another.'\" (Surah Al-Isra: 88). Their claim exposed their arrogance, not their ability.",
    "This ˹Quran˺ is nothing but ancient fables!\"": "They dismissed the Quran as mere legends and stories from ancient civilizations—fairy tales with no divine origin. This was their way of undermining its authority without actually engaging with its content. The truth is, the Quran contains knowledge that no human of that time could have known, and its linguistic miracle remains unmatched to this day."
  },
  32: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when they prayed, \"O Allah! If this is indeed the truth from You,": "This was the prayer of al-Nadr ibn al-Harith or Abu Jahl, showing extreme arrogance. Instead of saying, \"O Allah, if this is the truth, guide us to it,\" they asked for destruction upon themselves. A sincere person would seek guidance, not challenge Allah to punish them.",
    "then rain down stones upon us from the sky or overcome us with a painful punishment.\"": "They mockingly asked for the very punishment that destroyed previous nations—stones from the sky like what destroyed the people of Lot. This shows their complete rejection and their certainty that no punishment would come. They were gambling with their eternal souls out of pride and stubbornness. This is the height of foolishness—to challenge the Creator of the universe."
  },
  33: {
    "But Allah would never punish them while you ˹O Prophet˺ were in their midst.": "One reason Allah delayed their punishment was the presence of the Prophet ﷺ among them. Allah does not send mass destruction upon a people while His messenger is still living among them, calling them to guidance. This was a mercy—not for the disbelievers alone, but as part of Allah's way with prophets. The Prophet ﷺ was described as a mercy to the worlds, and his presence was a protection for them.",
    "Nor would He ever punish them if they prayed for forgiveness.": "Another protection from punishment is seeking forgiveness (istighfar). As long as people turn to Allah in repentance, He holds back His punishment. This shows Allah's immense mercy—He gives chance after chance. However, the pagans of Makkah were not actually seeking forgiveness sincerely; this verse may refer to the Muslims among them who did seek forgiveness, or it may be a general principle that istighfar prevents punishment."
  },
  34: {
    "And why should Allah not punish them while they hinder pilgrims from the Sacred Mosque,": "After explaining why punishment was delayed, Allah now explains why they deserve punishment. The Quraysh prevented Muslims from visiting the Ka'bah and performing pilgrimage. They blocked the believers from the most sacred place on earth—a place built by Ibrahim (Abraham) for the worship of Allah alone. This was a grave crime.",
    "claiming to be its rightful guardians?": "The Quraysh claimed they were the legitimate caretakers of the Ka'bah. They saw themselves as the religious authority of Arabia. But their guardianship was illegitimate because they had filled the Ka'bah with 360 idols and practiced all kinds of corruption.",
    "None has the right to guardianship except those mindful ˹of Allah˺,": "True guardianship of sacred places belongs to those who have taqwa—those who worship Allah alone, follow His commands, and maintain the sanctity of these places. The idolaters had no right to claim this honor.",
    "but most pagans do not know.": "They were ignorant of this reality. They assumed their ancestry and tribal status gave them religious authority. But in Allah's sight, honor comes through piety, not lineage."
  },
  35: {
    "Their prayer at the Sacred House was nothing but whistling and clapping.": "Instead of proper worship—standing in humility, bowing, prostrating, and supplicating to Allah—the pagans' so-called prayer consisted of whistling and clapping around the Ka'bah. Some would even circumambulate the Ka'bah naked, thinking this was pleasing to their gods. This was a mockery of true worship and a corruption of Ibrahim's legacy.",
    "So taste the punishment for your disbelief.": "Because of their false worship and rejection of the truth, they are told to taste the punishment. This refers both to their defeat at Badr and to the punishment awaiting them in the Hereafter. Their arrogant claim to be guardians of Allah's House while practicing such absurdities sealed their fate."
  },
  36: {
    "Surely the disbelievers spend their wealth to hinder others from the Path of Allah.": "The wealthy leaders of Quraysh spent enormous amounts of money to fight against Islam—funding armies, paying poets to mock the Prophet ﷺ, bribing people to oppose him, and supporting any effort to block the spread of Islam. After Badr, they used the profits from Abu Sufyan's caravan to finance the army that fought at Uhud.",
    "They will continue to spend to the point of regret.": "They will keep spending, but eventually, all that wealth will become a source of sorrow and regret. They will realize they wasted their money fighting against the truth. On the Day of Judgment, they will wish they had never spent a single coin against Islam.",
    "Then they will be defeated": "Despite all their spending and efforts, they will ultimately lose. This prophecy came true—Makkah was eventually conquered, the idols were destroyed, and Islam prevailed throughout Arabia and beyond.",
    "and the disbelievers will be driven into Hell.": "Their final destination is Hellfire. All the wealth they spent will not save them from eternal punishment. Instead, it will be counted against them as evidence of their opposition to Allah's religion."
  },
  37: {
    "so Allah may separate the evil from the good.": "One of Allah's purposes in these events is to distinguish between the good and the evil—between sincere believers and stubborn disbelievers. Tests and trials serve to clarify who truly believes and who is merely pretending or following the crowd.",
    "He will pile up the evil ones all together": "On the Day of Judgment, Allah will gather all the evil ones—their wealth, their deeds, and their leaders—and heap them all together.",
    "and then cast them into Hell.": "This pile of evil—people and their corrupted resources—will all be thrown into Hellfire. Nothing they accumulated will benefit them; instead, it will be fuel for their punishment.",
    "They are the ˹true˺ losers.": "Despite appearing successful in this world, they are the real losers. They lost their souls, their eternity, and any chance of salvation. Worldly success means nothing if it ends in eternal loss."
  },
  38: {
    "Tell the disbelievers that if they desist, their past will be forgiven.": "This is a remarkable offer of mercy. Despite all the torture, persecution, and warfare the pagans inflicted on Muslims, Allah offers them complete forgiveness if they simply stop and accept Islam. All their past crimes—including killing Muslims, stealing their property, and fighting against the Prophet ﷺ—would be erased. Islam wipes out all previous sins. The Prophet ﷺ said: \"Islam erases what came before it.\" (Sahih Muslim)",
    "But if they persist, then they have an example in those destroyed before them.": "If they continue their opposition, they should look at history. Previous nations that rejected their prophets were destroyed—the people of Noah, 'Ad, Thamud, the people of Lot, Pharaoh's people. The same fate awaits those who stubbornly fight against Allah's religion. History repeats itself for those who don't learn from it."
  },
  39: {
    "Fight against them until there is no more persecution—": "The believers are commanded to fight defensive battles until persecution (fitnah) is eliminated. Fitnah here refers to the religious persecution that prevents people from practicing Islam freely—torture, forced apostasy, and oppression based on faith. The goal is not to force people into Islam, but to create an environment where everyone can practice their faith without fear.",
    "and ˹your˺ devotion will be entirely to Allah.": "The ultimate objective is that religion (worship, obedience, way of life) belongs to Allah alone. This means establishing justice and freedom of worship, not forcing conversion. Once idolatry and persecution end, people can choose their faith freely.",
    "But if they desist, then surely Allah is All-Seeing of what they do.": "If they stop fighting and persecuting, Muslims should also stop fighting. Allah sees everything—He knows whether their cessation is genuine or just a tactical pause. He will judge them accordingly. This shows that Islam prefers peace when the enemy genuinely seeks it."
  },
  40: {
    "And if they do not comply, then know that Allah is your Protector.": "If the disbelievers refuse peace and continue their aggression, the believers should not worry. Allah is their Mawla—their Protector, Guardian, and Supporter. When Allah is on your side, no enemy can ultimately harm you.",
    "What an excellent Protector, and what an excellent Helper!": "Allah is praised as the best Protector and the best Helper. This provides comfort and confidence to the believers. With Allah's protection, they faced the mighty Quraysh and won at Badr. With Allah's help, a small band of believers eventually conquered all of Arabia. This phrase reminds believers that their success depends on Allah, not on military strength alone."
  },
  41: {
    "Know that whatever spoils you take, one-fifth is for Allah and the Messenger,": "This verse establishes the Islamic law for dividing war spoils (ghanimah). One-fifth (20%) of all spoils goes to specific categories, starting with Allah and His Messenger. This portion was used by the Prophet ﷺ for the needs of the Muslim community, state expenses, and spreading Islam. The remaining four-fifths (80%) is distributed among the fighters who participated in the battle.",
    "his close relatives,": "Part of the one-fifth goes to the relatives of the Prophet ﷺ—specifically Banu Hashim and Banu al-Muttalib. Since the Prophet's family was forbidden from receiving regular charity (zakat), this was a permissible source of support for them.",
    "orphans,": "Children who have lost their fathers and have no one to provide for them receive a share. Islam gives special attention to orphans, and the Prophet ﷺ said: \"I and the caretaker of an orphan will be in Paradise like this,\" and he held his two fingers together. (Sahih Bukhari)",
    "the poor,": "Those who are needy and struggling financially receive support from this portion. This ensures that the wealth gained in battle benefits the entire community, not just the fighters.",
    "and ˹needy˺ travellers,": "Ibn al-Sabil refers to travelers who are stranded or in need while on a journey, even if they are wealthy at home. They receive assistance to continue their travels.",
    "if you ˹truly˺ believe in Allah and what We revealed to Our servant on that decisive day when the two armies met ˹at Badr˺.": "Accepting this distribution system is tied to faith. If you truly believe in Allah and in the revelation given on the day of Badr—the Day of Furqan (criterion/distinction) when truth was separated from falsehood—then you will accept Allah's ruling without complaint.",
    "And Allah is Most Capable of everything.": "Allah has power over all things. He established this system, and He has the authority and wisdom to do so. Believers should submit to His commands, knowing His decisions are perfect."
  },
  42: {
    "˹Remember˺ when you were on the near side of the valley, your enemy on the far side, and the caravan was below you.": "This describes the positions at Badr. The Muslim army was on the side of the valley closer to Madinah, while the Quraysh army was on the far side. Abu Sufyan's caravan, which had escaped, was on the coastal route below. The scene was set for a confrontation that would change history.",
    "Even if the two armies had made an appointment ˹to meet˺, both would have certainly missed it.": "If the Muslims and Quraysh had deliberately planned to meet at that exact time and place, something would have gone wrong—miscommunication, delays, or other obstacles. The fact that they ended up facing each other was not coincidence but divine arrangement.",
    "Still it transpired so Allah may establish what He had destined—": "Allah brought them together to fulfill His decree. The battle was destined to happen to establish Islam and weaken its enemies. Nothing happens by accident in Allah's universe; everything follows His plan.",
    "that those who were to perish and those who were to survive might do so after the truth had been made clear to both.": "After Badr, everyone had clear evidence. Those who still rejected Islam after seeing Allah's help for the believers did so knowing the truth. Those who believed did so with certainty. No one could claim ignorance after such a clear demonstration of divine support.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah heard the prayers of both sides and knew the intentions of every heart. He responded according to His knowledge and wisdom, granting victory to those who deserved it."
  },
  43: {
    "˹Remember, O Prophet,˺ when Allah showed them in your dream as few in number.": "Before the battle, Allah showed the Prophet ﷺ a dream in which the enemy appeared to be few. This dream gave the Prophet ﷺ and, through him, the believers confidence. Dreams of prophets are a form of revelation, so this was Allah's way of preparing them psychologically.",
    "Had He shown them to you as many, you ˹believers˺ would have certainly faltered and disputed in the matter.": "If the Prophet ﷺ had seen the true size of the enemy (about 1,000 well-armed men against 313 Muslims), the believers might have lost courage and argued about whether to fight or retreat. Fear could have caused division and hesitation.",
    "But Allah spared you ˹from that˺.": "Allah protected them from this psychological burden. By showing the enemy as few, He preserved their unity and resolve. This was a mercy from Allah.",
    "Surely He knows best what is ˹hidden˺ in the heart.": "Allah knows the inner workings of every heart—fears, doubts, strengths, and weaknesses. He managed the situation perfectly based on His complete knowledge of human psychology."
  },
  44: {
    "Then when your armies met, Allah made them appear as few in your eyes,": "When the actual battle began, Allah continued this perception management. The believers saw the enemy as fewer than they actually were, which boosted their confidence to engage.",
    "and made you appear as few in theirs,": "Simultaneously, the Quraysh also saw the Muslims as fewer. This made them overconfident and less cautious. They underestimated the Muslims, which contributed to their defeat. When they realized the reality, it was too late.",
    "so Allah may establish what He had destined.": "Both perceptions served Allah's plan. The Muslims fought with courage; the Quraysh fought with arrogance. The result was exactly what Allah had decreed—a decisive Muslim victory.",
    "And to Allah ˹all˺ matters will be returned ˹for judgment˺.": "Ultimately, all affairs return to Allah. He controls outcomes, and He will judge everyone on the Day of Judgment. This reminder puts the battle in perspective—it was one event in a larger divine plan."
  },
  45: {
    "O believers! When you face an enemy, stand firm": "This is practical military and spiritual advice. When confronting an enemy force, the first instruction is to stand firm—don't panic, don't flee, maintain your positions. Steadfastness is essential for victory. An army that holds its ground is far more effective than one that wavers.",
    "and remember Allah often so you may triumph.": "Alongside physical steadfastness, the believers are commanded to remember Allah frequently. This includes making dhikr (remembrance), saying takbir (Allahu Akbar), making du'a, and keeping hearts connected to Allah. Victory comes from Allah, so maintaining spiritual connection during battle is crucial. The Prophet ﷺ and his companions would make du'a and dhikr even in the heat of battle. This combination of faith and action is the Islamic formula for success."
  },
  46: {
    "Obey Allah and His Messenger": "Success in any endeavor requires obedience to divine guidance. In battle especially, following the Prophet's commands and strategies is essential. Disobedience leads to disaster, as was seen later at the Battle of Uhud when some archers left their posts against the Prophet's orders.",
    "and do not dispute with one another, or you would be discouraged and weakened.": "Internal conflict is a recipe for defeat. When people argue and dispute, they lose focus, morale drops, and unity is broken. A united force is much stronger than a divided one. Allah warns that disputes lead to failure and loss of strength (\"your wind will depart\"—meaning your power and momentum will vanish).",
    "Persevere! Surely Allah is with those who persevere.": "Patience (sabr) is essential. Battles are difficult; there will be fear, exhaustion, and loss. Those who remain patient through these trials have Allah's support. This is a powerful motivation: Allah Himself is with the patient ones, aiding and protecting them."
  },
  47: {
    "Do not be like those ˹pagans˺ who left their homes arrogantly, only to be seen by people": "This refers to the Quraysh army that marched to Badr with arrogance and showmanship. They brought singers and musicians, slaughtered camels extravagantly, and boasted about their power. They wanted to impress people and intimidate the Muslims. Their motivation was pride and reputation, not any just cause.",
    "and to hinder others from Allah's Path.": "Their goal was to block Islam and prevent people from following the truth. They fought not to defend themselves but to crush a religious movement that threatened their power and way of life.",
    "And Allah is Fully Aware of what they do.": "Despite their outward display, Allah knew their true intentions. He was aware of their arrogance, their cruelty, and their objectives. This knowledge informed His judgment against them."
  },
  48: {
    "And ˹remember˺ when Satan made their ˹evil˺ deeds appealing to them, and said, \"No one can overcome you today.": "Satan (Iblis) appeared to the Quraysh, some scholars say in the form of Suraqah ibn Malik, a respected leader. He made their mission seem righteous and assured them they would be victorious. He beautified their evil intentions, making them confident in their superiority.",
    "I am surely by your side.\"": "Satan promised to support them and stand with them. This is how he operates—he encourages sin by promising support and minimizing consequences. He told them he was their ally and protector.",
    "But when the two forces faced off, he cowered and said, \"I have absolutely nothing to do with you.": "When battle began and Satan saw the angels descending to help the Muslims, he fled in terror. He completely abandoned those he had just promised to help. This is the reality of Satan—he makes promises he never intends to keep. On the Day of Judgment, he will similarly disown all his followers (Surah Ibrahim: 22).",
    "I certainly see what you do not see.": "Satan could see the angels that humans couldn't see. He knew the divine forces were against the Quraysh and that destruction was coming.",
    "I truly fear Allah, for Allah is severe in punishment.\"": "In his moment of fear, Satan acknowledged Allah's power and punishment. He fled to save himself, caring nothing for those he had misled. This shows that even Satan fears Allah and knows the truth—but he still disobeys and misleads others. His fear didn't lead him to repentance, only to self-preservation."
  },
  49: {
    "˹Remember˺ when the hypocrites and those with sickness in their hearts said, \"These ˹believers˺ are deluded by their faith.\"": "Some hypocrites in Madinah and those with weak or diseased faith mocked the believers going to Badr. They saw 313 poorly equipped men marching against a thousand well-armed Quraysh warriors and thought the Muslims were crazy. They said religion had deceived them into a suicidal mission. This reflects how people of weak faith cannot understand the power of trust in Allah.",
    "But whoever puts their trust in Allah, surely Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.": "Allah responds to their mockery by affirming the power of tawakkul (trust in Allah). Those who truly rely on Allah are never deluded—because Allah is Al-Aziz (Almighty, invincible) and Al-Hakeem (All-Wise, making perfect decisions). Allah proved the mockers wrong when the Muslims won a miraculous victory at Badr."
  },
  50: {
    "If only you could see when the angels take the souls of the disbelievers, beating their faces and backs, ˹saying,˺": "This verse describes the horrifying moment of death for those who die in disbelief. The angels responsible for taking their souls do not do so gently. They strike the faces (representing their arrogance and defiance) and backs (representing their turning away from the truth) of the disbelievers. This is a glimpse into the unseen reality of death for those who reject Allah.",
    "\"Taste the torment of burning!": "As they take their souls, the angels announce the punishment that awaits: the burning fire of Hell. The word \"taste\" suggests this is just the beginning—an appetizer of the eternal suffering to come. This should serve as a powerful warning for anyone considering a life of disbelief."
  },
  51: {
    "This is ˹the reward˺ for what your hands have done.": "The punishment they receive is a direct result of their own choices and actions. They earned this fate through their deeds—their disbelief, persecution of believers, and rejection of guidance. No one else is to blame.",
    "And Allah is never unjust to ˹His˺ creation.\"": "Allah does not wrong anyone even slightly. Whatever punishment comes is perfectly deserved and proportionate. Allah gave them chances, sent messengers, and revealed clear signs. They chose to reject, so they earned their punishment. Allah's justice is perfect and complete."
  },
  52: {
    "Their fate is that of the people of Pharaoh and those before them—": "The Quraysh's fate mirrors that of Pharaoh and his people, as well as other destroyed nations before them. History repeats itself: those who reject Allah's messengers and fight against truth meet similar ends.",
    "they all disbelieved in Allah's signs, so Allah seized them for their sins.": "The common factor in all these destructions was disbelief in Allah's signs—the miracles, revelations, and clear proofs sent through messengers. Because of their sins of rejection and oppression, Allah seized them with punishment.",
    "Indeed, Allah is All-Powerful, severe in punishment.": "Allah is Al-Qawiy (All-Powerful)—no one can resist His punishment or escape His grasp. When He decides to punish, nothing can prevent it. And His punishment is severe for those who deserve it."
  },
  53: {
    "This is because Allah would never discontinue His favour to a people until they discontinue their faith.": "This is an important divine principle: Allah does not take away His blessings from a people unless they themselves change. If they were blessed with security, wealth, or guidance, Allah doesn't remove these until they become ungrateful, sinful, or faithless. The Quraysh were honored as guardians of the Ka'bah and leaders of Arabia, but they forfeited these blessings through their disbelief and persecution of Muslims.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah hears what they say—their mockery, their plots, their rejection—and He knows what they hide in their hearts. His decisions are based on complete knowledge of their state."
  },
  54: {
    "That was the case with Pharaoh's people and those before them—they all rejected the signs of their Lord,": "Again, the pattern is emphasized: Pharaoh's people and earlier nations all denied the signs sent to them through their messengers. Despite clear miracles and evidence, they stubbornly rejected.",
    "so We destroyed them for their sins": "Their sins brought their destruction. It was not arbitrary or unjust—it was earned through their own choices. Allah gave them time to repent, but they persisted in evil.",
    "and drowned Pharaoh's people.": "Pharaoh and his army were drowned in the sea while chasing Moses and the Israelites. This is one of the most famous examples of divine punishment in history—a mighty empire destroyed in a single day.",
    "They were all wrongdoers.": "The verse concludes by confirming that all these destroyed peoples were wrongdoers (zalimeen). They oppressed others, rejected truth, and transgressed against Allah's commands. Their punishment was justice."
  },
  55: {
    "Indeed, the worst of all beings in the sight of Allah are those who persist in disbelief, never to have faith—": "Allah declares that the worst creatures in His sight are those who stubbornly disbelieve with no intention of ever accepting faith. They have sealed their hearts against guidance. They are worse than animals because animals follow their nature, while these people actively reject the truth despite having reason and evidence. This applies to those whose disbelief is final and obstinate."
  },
  56: {
    "˹namely˺ those with whom you ˹O Prophet˺ have entered into treaties, but they violate them every time, not fearing the consequences.": "This specifically describes certain Jewish tribes in Madinah (like Banu Qaynuqa and Banu Qurayza) who had treaties with the Prophet ﷺ but repeatedly broke them. Every time a treaty was made, they violated it—helping enemies, breaking agreements, and plotting against Muslims. They had no fear of Allah (taqwa), which would have prevented such betrayal. Treaty violation is a serious matter in Islam, combining lying, betrayal, and treachery."
  },
  57: {
    "If you ever encounter them in battle, make a fearsome example of them,": "If war becomes necessary against these treaty-breakers, the Muslims are commanded to defeat them decisively and make an example of them. The punishment should be severe enough to serve as a deterrent.",
    "so perhaps those who would follow them may be deterred.": "The purpose is not revenge but prevention. By dealing firmly with treaty-breakers, others who might consider similar betrayal will be discouraged. This is a practical approach to maintaining order and discouraging treachery. When people see that betrayal has serious consequences, they think twice before committing it."
  },
  58: {
    "And if you ˹O Prophet˺ see signs of betrayal by a people,": "If there are clear indications that a treaty partner is planning to betray the agreement—through intelligence, suspicious actions, or partial violations—the Muslims should not wait to be attacked.",
    "respond by openly terminating your treaty with them.": "Instead of attacking suddenly while technically still in a treaty (which would be betrayal), the Muslims must first openly and clearly announce that the treaty is terminated. This gives fair warning and maintains Islamic integrity. Islam forbids surprise attacks on treaty partners—even if they are suspected of treachery, the Muslim response must be transparent.",
    "Surely Allah does not like those who betray.": "Betrayal is hateful to Allah. This applies to everyone—Muslims must not be treacherous even against enemies who might be planning treachery against them. The Islamic standard is honesty and clarity in all dealings, even in war."
  },
  59: {
    "Do not let those disbelievers think they are not within reach.": "Some disbelievers who escaped from Badr or avoided confrontation might think they have escaped Allah's punishment or Muslim justice. This verse warns them not to be deluded.",
    "They will have no escape.": "No one can escape Allah's reach. Whether in this world through Muslim forces or in the Hereafter through divine punishment, those who oppose Islam will face consequences. Distance or time does not grant immunity."
  },
  60: {
    "Prepare against them what you ˹believers˺ can of ˹military˺ power and cavalry": "Muslims are commanded to prepare militarily to the best of their ability. In the Prophet's time, this meant horses, weapons, and trained fighters. In modern times, it includes all forms of legitimate defense capability. The Prophet ﷺ explained that \"power\" includes archery (skill in projectile weapons—which today would include firearms and missiles). He said: \"Verily, strength is in shooting.\" (Sahih Muslim)",
    "to deter Allah's enemies and your enemies": "The primary purpose of military strength is deterrence—preventing war by being too strong to attack. When enemies see that Muslims are capable of defending themselves, they are less likely to attack. This is a defensive, not aggressive, doctrine.",
    "as well as other enemies unknown to you but known to Allah.": "There may be enemies planning harm that Muslims are not aware of. Military readiness deters even these hidden threats. Allah knows all enemies, seen and unseen, so preparation serves broader purposes than Muslims might realize.",
    "Whatever you spend in the cause of Allah will be paid to you in full and you will not be wronged.": "Every penny spent on legitimate defense is an investment with Allah. It will be rewarded fully, with no loss or injustice. This encourages Muslims to invest in their community's security, knowing it is both a religious duty and a source of reward."
  },
  61: {
    "If the enemy is inclined towards peace, make peace with them.": "This is a fundamental principle: if the enemy genuinely seeks peace, Muslims should accept it. Islam does not promote endless warfare. Peace is preferred when it is available on acceptable terms. This verse was applied when the Prophet ﷺ accepted the Treaty of Hudaybiyyah, even though its terms seemed unfavorable at the time. That peace led to the eventual conquest of Makkah without bloodshed.",
    "And put your trust in Allah.": "When making peace, there's always a risk that the enemy might betray the agreement. But Muslims should trust in Allah and proceed with peace. Taking the risk of peace is better than the certainty of continued war.",
    "Indeed, He ˹alone˺ is the All-Hearing, All-Knowing.": "Allah hears the peace proposals and knows the true intentions behind them. If the enemy is sincere, peace will benefit everyone. If they are deceiving, Allah knows and will deal with them accordingly. Muslims are not responsible for reading hearts—only for acting honorably."
  },
  62: {
    "But if their intention is only to deceive you, then Allah is certainly sufficient for you.": "If the enemy's peace offer is actually a trap or stalling tactic, Allah will be enough protection. Muslims should not let fear of deception prevent them from pursuing peace. Allah is the ultimate protector.",
    "He is the One Who has supported you with His help and with the believers.": "Allah reminds the Prophet ﷺ of past support—divine assistance at Badr and the loyal believers who sacrificed everything for Islam. The same Allah who provided that support will continue to protect against any deception."
  },
  63: {
    "He brought their hearts together.": "Allah united the hearts of the believers—particularly the Aws and Khazraj tribes of Madinah, who had been enemies for generations before Islam. Their unity was a miracle.",
    "Had you spent all the riches in the earth, you could not have united their hearts.": "No amount of money or worldly effort could have achieved this unity. The Aws and Khazraj had deep-rooted hatred and blood feuds. Only Allah could transform that enmity into brotherhood.",
    "But Allah has united them.": "It was purely Allah's doing. Through Islam and the guidance of the Prophet ﷺ, Allah created a bond stronger than tribal ties or blood relations. This brotherhood (ukhuwwah) is one of Islam's greatest achievements.",
    "Indeed, He is Almighty, All-Wise.": "Allah has the power to change hearts and the wisdom to do so in the perfect way. His uniting of the believers was both a display of power and wisdom—creating a community that would carry Islam to the world."
  },
  64: {
    "O Prophet! Allah is sufficient for you and for the believers who follow you.": "This is a powerful statement of reassurance. Allah alone is enough—for the Prophet ﷺ and for all the believers. They don't need large numbers, great wealth, or powerful allies. With Allah as their supporter, they have everything they need. This verse gave confidence to the early Muslims who were few in number and resources. It continues to inspire believers today: when you have Allah, you have enough."
  },
  65: {
    "O Prophet! Motivate the believers to fight.": "The Prophet ﷺ is commanded to encourage and inspire the believers to engage in battle when necessary. The word 'harriḍ' means to urge, motivate, and stir up enthusiasm. A leader's role is not just to command but to inspire. The Prophet ﷺ would personally encourage his companions before battles, reminding them of Paradise and Allah's rewards. This motivation is essential because fighting requires courage that goes beyond natural human inclination.",
    "If there are twenty steadfast among you, they will overcome two hundred.": "Allah promises that twenty patient, steadfast believers can defeat two hundred enemies—a ratio of 1 to 10. This was the initial standard set by Allah, requiring immense faith and perseverance. The key word is 'ṣābirūn' (steadfast/patient ones). Victory doesn't come from numbers alone but from the quality of fighters—their faith, patience, and determination.",
    "And if there are one hundred of you, they will overcome one thousand of the disbelievers,": "The same ratio applies at larger scales: one hundred believers can defeat one thousand disbelievers. This reflects the reality at Badr, where 313 Muslims defeated approximately 1,000 Quraysh fighters. When believers have true faith and patience, Allah multiplies their effectiveness.",
    "for they are a people who do not comprehend.": "The disbelievers lack true understanding. They don't comprehend the reality of life and death, the Hereafter, or the power of Allah. A believer who knows they're fighting for Allah and that death means Paradise fights differently than someone fighting only for worldly gains. This spiritual advantage is decisive."
  },
  66: {
    "Now Allah has lightened your burden, for He knows that there is weakness in you.": "Allah, in His mercy, reduced the requirement. He acknowledged that there is weakness among the believers—not everyone can maintain the standard of fighting ten times their number. This shows Allah's understanding and compassion. He doesn't burden people beyond their capacity. As the Muslim community grew to include people of varying levels of faith and strength, the standard was adjusted.",
    "So if there are a hundred steadfast among you, they will overcome two hundred.": "The new ratio is 1 to 2 instead of 1 to 10. One hundred believers are now expected to defeat two hundred enemies. This is still challenging but more achievable for average believers.",
    "And if there be one thousand, they will overcome two thousand, by Allah's Will.": "At larger numbers, the same ratio applies. The phrase 'by Allah's Will' (bi-idhnillāh) is crucial—victory always depends on Allah's permission. No military calculation guarantees victory; only Allah determines outcomes.",
    "And Allah is with the steadfast.": "This is both a promise and an encouragement. Those who remain patient and steadfast in battle have Allah's special support. His 'being with them' means His aid, protection, guidance, and blessings. This divine companionship is worth more than any number of soldiers or weapons."
  },
  67: {
    "It is not fit for a prophet that he should take captives until he has thoroughly subdued the land.": "After the Battle of Badr, the Muslims captured about 70 prisoners from the Quraysh. The Prophet ﷺ consulted his companions about what to do. Abu Bakr suggested ransoming them, while Umar suggested executing them to weaken the enemy permanently. The Prophet ﷺ chose ransom. This verse contains a gentle correction: in the early stage of establishing Islam, when enemies were still powerful and dangerous, the priority should have been to decisively weaken the enemy, not to collect ransom money. 'Thoroughly subdued' (yuthkhina) means to establish firm control and break enemy power.",
    "You ˹believers˺ settled with the fleeting gains of this world,": "By choosing ransom, the Muslims prioritized immediate financial gain (the ransom money) over the greater strategic goal. The 'fleeting gains of this world' (araḍ al-dunyā) refers to temporary, worldly benefits that quickly pass away.",
    "while Allah's aim ˹for you˺ is the Hereafter.": "Allah wanted something greater for them—eternal rewards and the complete establishment of Islam. The focus should have been on what benefits the Hereafter and the long-term mission, not short-term profit.",
    "Allah is Almighty, All-Wise.": "Despite this correction, Allah's power and wisdom remain supreme. He is Al-Aziz (Almighty) and Al-Hakeem (All-Wise). His guidance, even when correcting, comes from perfect knowledge and wisdom."
  },
  68: {
    "Had it not been for a prior decree from Allah,": "Allah had already decreed that the ransom would be permissible for this ummah, or that the Muslims at Badr would not be punished for this ijtihad (sincere judgment), or that war spoils would be lawful. Without this prior divine decree protecting them—",
    "you would have certainly been disciplined with a tremendous punishment for whatever ˹ransom˺ you have taken.": "The decision to take ransom, though made with good intentions, could have resulted in severe divine punishment. This shows how serious the matter was. However, Allah's prior decree prevented this punishment. When Umar heard this verse, he wept, and the Prophet ﷺ also cried, recognizing how close they had come to divine displeasure. This incident teaches that even sincere decisions by good people can sometimes be wrong, and that Allah's mercy often saves believers from the consequences of their mistakes."
  },
  69: {
    "Now enjoy what you have taken, for it is lawful and good.": "After the correction and warning, Allah shows His mercy by making the ransom permissible. The word 'halālan' (lawful) and 'ṭayyiban' (good/pure) confirm that what they took is allowed and blessed. They should not feel guilty about using it. This is a beautiful example of Allah's forgiveness—He corrects, warns, but then pardons and allows them to benefit.",
    "And be mindful of Allah.": "Going forward, they should maintain taqwa (God-consciousness) in all decisions. They should always consider what Allah wants, not just what seems beneficial in the moment.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Allah forgives their mistake and shows them mercy. These names (Al-Ghafūr, Al-Rahīm) provide comfort after the stern warning. Allah's forgiveness is vast, and His mercy encompasses those who turn to Him with sincere hearts."
  },
  70: {
    "O Prophet! Tell the captives in your custody, \"If Allah finds goodness in your hearts,": "The Prophet ﷺ is instructed to give the prisoners of war a message of hope. Despite being captured enemies, the door to Allah's mercy is still open to them. The condition is that Allah must find 'goodness' (khayr) in their hearts—sincerity, potential for faith, or a genuine inclination toward truth.",
    "He will give you better than what has been taken from you,": "If they become sincere, Allah will replace whatever wealth they lost in ransom with something better. This happened to some of the Badr captives who later accepted Islam. Abbas, the Prophet's uncle, was one of the captives. After he accepted Islam, Allah blessed him with abundant wealth far exceeding what he had paid in ransom.",
    "and forgive you.": "Beyond material compensation, Allah offers forgiveness for their past—including their fighting against the Muslims. Islam erases previous sins. This is an incredible offer of mercy to former enemies.",
    "For Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.\"": "The message ends with these reassuring names of Allah. No matter what they had done—fighting against the Prophet ﷺ, persecuting Muslims—Allah's forgiveness and mercy are available to those who sincerely turn to Him."
  },
  71: {
    "But if their intention is only to betray you ˹O Prophet˺,": "Some captives might accept the offer falsely, pretending to convert while planning to betray the Muslims once released. This verse addresses that possibility.",
    "they sought to betray Allah before.": "This is not new behavior for them—they already betrayed Allah by rejecting His messenger and fighting against the truth. Their previous betrayal is on record.",
    "But He gave you power over them.": "Their earlier betrayal of Allah resulted in their defeat and capture at Badr. Allah gave the Muslims power over them as a consequence of their treachery against divine guidance. If they try to betray again, the same fate or worse awaits them.",
    "And Allah is All-Knowing, All-Wise.": "Allah knows their true intentions—whether their acceptance is sincere or a deception. Nothing is hidden from Him. And He is All-Wise in how He deals with both the sincere and the hypocritical."
  },
  72: {
    "Those who believed, emigrated, and strived with their wealth and lives in the cause of Allah,": "This describes the Muhājirūn—the emigrants from Makkah. They believed in Allah, left their homes and properties behind, and struggled with everything they had for Islam. Their sacrifice was complete: they gave up wealth, comfort, family ties, and risked their lives.",
    "as well as those who gave them shelter and help—": "This describes the Anṣār—the helpers of Madinah. They welcomed the emigrants, shared their homes and wealth, and supported them in every way. The Prophet ﷺ established brotherhood (mu'ākhāh) between each emigrant and a helper, creating bonds stronger than blood.",
    "they are truly guardians of one another.": "These two groups have a special relationship of walāyah (guardianship, loyalty, mutual support). In the early Islamic state, this was so strong that they even inherited from each other despite not being blood relatives. They were bound by faith, not just blood.",
    "As for those who believed but did not emigrate, you have no obligations to them until they emigrate.": "Muslims who accepted Islam but remained in Makkah (or other non-Muslim territories) were not part of this political guardianship system. The Islamic state in Madinah had no formal obligations to protect them or include them in inheritance until they made hijrah. This was specific to that context when emigration was obligatory.",
    "But if they seek your help ˹against persecution˺ in faith, it is your obligation to help them,": "However, if these believers were persecuted for their faith and called for help, the Muslims in Madinah were obligated to assist them. Religious solidarity requires helping fellow believers who are oppressed.",
    "except against people bound with you in a treaty.": "There's one exception: if the persecutors have a peace treaty with the Muslims, the Muslims cannot fight them to help the oppressed believers. Treaties must be honored. The Muslims would need to find other ways to help—diplomacy, negotiation, ransom—but not military action against treaty partners.",
    "Allah is All-Seeing of what you do.": "Allah watches all actions and intentions. He sees who honors their obligations, who helps the oppressed, and who maintains treaties. Everyone will be held accountable."
  },
  73: {
    "As for the disbelievers, they are guardians of one another.": "Just as believers support each other, the disbelievers also form a united front against Islam. Despite their internal differences, when it comes to opposing the truth, they cooperate and assist each other. This is a reality Muslims must recognize.",
    "And unless you ˹believers˺ act likewise, there will be great oppression and corruption in the land.": "If the Muslims don't maintain their own unity and mutual support, the consequences will be severe: fitnah (trials, persecution, chaos) and fasād (corruption, disorder). When believers are divided while enemies are united, the enemies dominate, and injustice spreads. Muslim unity is not just recommended—it's essential for preventing global corruption and oppression."
  },
  74: {
    "Those who believed, migrated, and struggled in the cause of Allah,": "Once again, the Muhājirūn are honored—those who combined faith with action, leaving everything familiar to establish Islam in a new land and fighting in Allah's cause.",
    "and those who gave ˹them˺ shelter and help,": "The Anṣār are equally honored—their generosity, sacrifice, and unwavering support made the success of Islam possible. Without them, the emigrants would have had nowhere to go.",
    "they are the true believers.": "This is a powerful certification from Allah Himself. These are not just nominal believers or those who simply claim faith—they are 'al-mu'minūna ḥaqqan' (the believers in truth/reality). Their actions proved their faith. This sets the standard for what genuine faith looks like.",
    "They will have forgiveness": "Despite all their sacrifices and good deeds, they still need Allah's forgiveness. This shows that even the best Muslims rely on Allah's mercy, not their deeds alone. Forgiveness is granted for any shortcomings.",
    "and an honourable provision.": "In addition to forgiveness, they receive rizqun karīm—a noble, generous provision. This refers to the blessings of Paradise: eternal comfort, honor, and pleasure that is pure and dignified. Their reward matches the nobility of their sacrifice."
  },
  75: {
    "And those who later believed, migrated, and struggled alongside you,": "This addresses those who accepted Islam after the initial group of Muhājirūn and Anṣār—the later emigrants and converts who joined the Muslim community and participated in jihad. They came later but made the same sacrifices.",
    "they are also with you.": "They are included in the community of believers with the same rights and status. Being early or late to Islam doesn't create different classes—all sincere believers who fulfill their obligations are united.",
    "But only blood relatives are now entitled to inherit from one another, as ordained by Allah.": "Initially, the bond between Muhājirūn and Anṣār was so strong that they could inherit from each other even without blood relation. This verse abrogates that ruling. Now, inheritance returns to blood relatives (ulul-arḥām) as specified in other verses about Islamic inheritance law. The spiritual brotherhood remains, but legal inheritance follows family lines.",
    "Surely Allah has ˹full˺ knowledge of everything.": "Allah knows the wisdom behind this change. He knows all relationships, rights, and what is best for the community. His laws are based on perfect knowledge—of human nature, family bonds, and social harmony. This verse concludes Surah Al-Anfal by affirming Allah's comprehensive knowledge, reminding believers that all these rulings come from the One who knows everything visible and hidden."
  }
};